{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti chapter 10, verse 8, Manu states that the son born from a Brāhmaṇa man and a Śūdra woman is a Niṣāda, who is also called a Pāraśava.**[^1]\n\nThis occurs in a passage classifying offspring from unions between higher-caste men (*anuloma* marriages) and women of lower castes:\n\n> [p-173ba2] From a Brahmana on a Vaishya maiden, a son named `Ambaṣṭha` is born; on a Shudra maiden, a `Niṣāda`, who is also called a `Pāraśava`. // Mn_10.8 //\n\nThe text specifies \"son\" here (as with other examples), though the broader context discusses *mixed castes* (verses 6–12). Later verses (e.g., Mn_10.10, 10.41) group such *pratiloma*-adjacent offspring as base-born with Śūdra-like Dharma.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-173ba2).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-370124).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-0ac1e6).",
